storyFeed.headline: Google going strong, but maybe not for long.
storyFeed.body: Google has some concerns to address the balance of this year, and beyond. Over the long run, the consensus analyst recommendation for Google as a 'strong buy' is warranted as the company continues driving a healthy double-digit top line growth. But that doesn't mean there won't be a hurdle, or three, to overcome along the way.

storyFeed.headline: Ad revenues still primary source of Google revenue.
storyFeed.body: Investors were encouraged by a healthy gain in the number of people looking at Google's ads, even as the average prices for those marketing messages extended a three-and-half year slump. The market also had been bracing for more disappointing numbers, triggering a 'relief rally' when the results weren't as bad as feared, BGC Partners analyst Colin Gillis said.

storyFeed.headline: Cloud gives Microsoft significant boost
storyFeed.body: Microsoft’s share price has made significant gains over the past month, as the company has shared more details about its cloud business. Fiscal third-quarter results showed its success in its commercial cloud business was generating about $6.3 billion a year in revenue. At a developers’ conference last week, Microsoft also disclosed plans to grow that business to about $20 billion in revenue by 2018.

storyFeed.headline: Microsoft buys stylus company N-Trig
storyFeed.body: Microsoft has bought the stylus and display interface technology for the Surface Pro 3 from the company that made it. Microsoft on Friday confirmed it bought the technology from Israel-based N-Trig. According to positive media reports, Microsoft bought the technology for $30 million to grow its foray into mobile computing.
